CALL PURPOSE: Assistance with creating a report in PC Recruiter

BUSINESS CONTEXT.Current challenges/pain points: Creating a report that captures all activities and candidates in a pipeline

RELATIONSHIP MAPPING.Previous interactions referenced: Going back and forth with Tyler

resolution_steps_taken: Assisted in creating a custom applicant tracking report
Provided instructions on how to use the report
Helped resolve issues with position ID and date range

key_quotes: I am trying to create a report that captures all of the activities and candidates in a pipeline.
And then when I went to export into an Excel, it didn't have any information.
I copied and pasted the job in there. Yeah, because that one just wanted the actual ID number.
If you use filter by job title, you could have more than one job with that title. So that may not be ideal.

qa_pairs.question: What's going on?
qa_pairs.answer: I am trying to create a report that captures all of the activities and candidates in a pipeline. And so I went in and I followed the instructions for the new pipeline report. And I thought I put in everything I needed to. And then when I went to export into an Excel, it didn't have any information.

qa_pairs.question: What filters are you using?
qa_pairs.answer: I put all of the steps in the moment let me just pull it up okay if you don't need all the steps you don't have to even select them so under when you go into the report where it says search params under that heading what is the date range that you're using?

qa_pairs.question: What is the date range that you're using?
What is the status are you nearing it by a particular position?
qa_pairs.answer: Yeah, so underneath filters you can narrow by a particular job if you want and you probably want to use position ID rather than title if you're looking for a particular job. And then if the jobs already closed or filled you'll need to clear out the filter by job status. But you don't have to narrow by any steps if you want all of them.
